[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":2247},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":2223,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":2232},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20230513\u002F284079926\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":17,"date":2207,"description":2208,"extension":2209,"lang":2210,"meta":2211,"navigation":612,"path":2212,"readingMinutes":2213,"seo":2214,"standalone":2215,"stem":2216,"tags":2217,"tldr":2220,"updated":2207,"url":2221,"__hash__":2222},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types.md","Can't Use TypeScript? Don't Worry — You Can Still Annotate Types With JSDoc","1001536289",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":2190},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,34,37,40,48,52,60,86,93,99,102,106,109,169,176,182,185,190,201,289,296,301,304,311,401,406,417,503,509,522,628,631,635,642,711,714,720,723,729,764,768,775,780,821,826,829,835,839,887,893,897,945,951,955,1014,1019,1022,1027,1031,1115,1118,1248,1253,1256,1262,1265,1376,1381,1388,1497,1501,1515,1567,1573,1801,1804,1810,1823,1879,1882,2039,2056,2110,2114,2117,2159,2168,2172,2175,2183,2186],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"JavaScript","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fn4QxX62.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"If your company's project can't use TypeScript but you still want something like TypeScript's type checking, give JSDoc a try. With JSDoc you can annotate types and get checks that feel a lot like TypeScript.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"whats-jsdoc","What's JSDoc?",[12,32,33],{},"Let's start with what JSDoc actually is. JSDoc stands for \"JavaScript Documentation\" — it's a tool built specifically for documenting JavaScript.",[12,35,36],{},"So what can it do? Basically it helps you annotate things: types, parameters, return values, and so on. Before TypeScript existed, JSDoc was a really handy tool — and honestly it was good enough to get the job done.",[12,38,39],{},"So let's take a look at how to use it. Before we start though, a quick note about my IDE — I'm using Visual Studio Code, the best IDE on the planet (in my humble opinion), and its JSDoc support is excellent. So all my examples here are in VSCode.",[41,42,45],"callout",{"title":43,"type":44},"Note","note",[12,46,47],{},"JSDoc has been around for a long time — since roughly 1999 — so it actually predates TypeScript.",[20,49,51],{"id":50},"setup","Setup",[12,53,54,55,59],{},"First, create a project in VSCode called ",[56,57,58],"code",{},"jsdoc-demo"," and initialize npm inside it:",[61,62,67],"pre",{"className":63,"code":64,"language":65,"meta":66,"style":66},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","npm init -y\n","bash","",[56,68,69],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,71,74,78,82],"span",{"class":72,"line":73},"line",1,[70,75,77],{"class":76},"smYoP","npm",[70,79,81],{"class":80},"sWayO"," init",[70,83,85],{"class":84},"stw71"," -y\n",[12,87,88,89,92],{},"Then create an ",[56,90,91],{},"index.js"," file. Your project structure should look like this:",[12,94,95],{},[15,96],{"alt":97,"src":98},"init","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fv73vEgs.png",[12,100,101],{},"Once that's ready, let's keep going.",[20,103,105],{"id":104},"how-to-write-jsdoc","How to Write JSDoc",[12,107,108],{},"Writing JSDoc isn't hard. Here's a bit of example code to start with:",[61,110,114],{"className":111,"code":112,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","const sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n","js",[56,115,116,146,163],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,117,118,122,126,129,133,137,140,143],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,119,121],{"class":120},"sOudu","const",[70,123,125],{"class":124},"scAaK"," sayHi",[70,127,128],{"class":120}," =",[70,130,132],{"class":131},"s8XSl"," (",[70,134,136],{"class":135},"syBk-","name",[70,138,139],{"class":131},") ",[70,141,142],{"class":120},"=>",[70,144,145],{"class":131}," {\n",[70,147,149,152,155,157,160],{"class":72,"line":148},2,[70,150,151],{"class":120},"  return",[70,153,154],{"class":80}," `Hi, ${",[70,156,136],{"class":131},[70,158,159],{"class":80},"}`",[70,161,162],{"class":131},";\n",[70,164,166],{"class":72,"line":165},3,[70,167,168],{"class":131},"};\n",[12,170,171,172,175],{},"So how do you annotate it? You just type ",[56,173,174],{},"\u002F**"," above the function, and our mighty VSCode will suggest a JSDoc comment for you:",[12,177,178],{},[15,179],{"alt":180,"src":181},"JSDoc comment","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FKPLD9M6.png",[12,183,184],{},"Hit Enter and it'll auto-generate the JSDoc comment, like this:",[12,186,187],{},[15,188],{"alt":180,"src":189},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FUN5U3wr.png",[12,191,192,193,196,197,200],{},"Pretty convenient, right? You can see VSCode generated ",[56,194,195],{},"@param {*} name"," and ",[56,198,199],{},"@returns"," for us. So how do we fill these in? It's simple — usually we describe what the function does, the type of each parameter, and the type of the return value. So you'd write it like this:",[61,202,204],{"className":111,"code":203,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[56,205,206,212,217,234,246,252,271,284],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,207,208],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,209,211],{"class":210},"sGBqm","\u002F**\n",[70,213,214],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,215,216],{"class":210}," * Greeting function\n",[70,218,219,222,225,228,231],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,220,221],{"class":210}," * ",[70,223,224],{"class":120},"@param",[70,226,227],{"class":76}," { string }",[70,229,230],{"class":131}," name",[70,232,233],{"class":210}," The name\n",[70,235,237,239,241,243],{"class":72,"line":236},4,[70,238,221],{"class":210},[70,240,199],{"class":120},[70,242,227],{"class":76},[70,244,245],{"class":210}," Hi, ${name}\n",[70,247,249],{"class":72,"line":248},5,[70,250,251],{"class":210}," *\u002F\n",[70,253,255,257,259,261,263,265,267,269],{"class":72,"line":254},6,[70,256,121],{"class":120},[70,258,125],{"class":124},[70,260,128],{"class":120},[70,262,132],{"class":131},[70,264,136],{"class":135},[70,266,139],{"class":131},[70,268,142],{"class":120},[70,270,145],{"class":131},[70,272,274,276,278,280,282],{"class":72,"line":273},7,[70,275,151],{"class":120},[70,277,154],{"class":80},[70,279,136],{"class":131},[70,281,159],{"class":80},[70,283,162],{"class":131},[70,285,287],{"class":72,"line":286},8,[70,288,168],{"class":131},[12,290,291,292,295],{},"Now when you hover your mouse over ",[56,293,294],{},"sayHi",", a tooltip shows up:",[12,297,298],{},[15,299],{"alt":294,"src":300},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fz88Ygca.png",[12,302,303],{},"So whenever you use this function somewhere else, JSDoc reminds you what it does, what parameter types it expects, and what it returns. That saves you a ton of time digging through the function to figure out what it's for, what to pass in, and what comes back.",[12,305,306,307,310],{},"JSDoc doesn't stop there, though. You can also use ",[56,308,309],{},"@example"," to show how the function is used:",[61,312,314],{"className":111,"code":313,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[56,315,316,320,324,336,346,353,361,365,383,396],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,317,318],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,319,211],{"class":210},[70,321,322],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,323,216],{"class":210},[70,325,326,328,330,332,334],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,327,221],{"class":210},[70,329,224],{"class":120},[70,331,227],{"class":76},[70,333,230],{"class":131},[70,335,233],{"class":210},[70,337,338,340,342,344],{"class":72,"line":236},[70,339,221],{"class":210},[70,341,199],{"class":120},[70,343,227],{"class":76},[70,345,245],{"class":210},[70,347,348,350],{"class":72,"line":248},[70,349,221],{"class":210},[70,351,352],{"class":120},"@example\n",[70,354,355,358],{"class":72,"line":254},[70,356,357],{"class":210}," * sayHi('John');",[70,359,360],{"class":210}," \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n",[70,362,363],{"class":72,"line":273},[70,364,251],{"class":210},[70,366,367,369,371,373,375,377,379,381],{"class":72,"line":286},[70,368,121],{"class":120},[70,370,125],{"class":124},[70,372,128],{"class":120},[70,374,132],{"class":131},[70,376,136],{"class":135},[70,378,139],{"class":131},[70,380,142],{"class":120},[70,382,145],{"class":131},[70,384,386,388,390,392,394],{"class":72,"line":385},9,[70,387,151],{"class":120},[70,389,154],{"class":80},[70,391,136],{"class":131},[70,393,159],{"class":80},[70,395,162],{"class":131},[70,397,399],{"class":72,"line":398},10,[70,400,168],{"class":131},[12,402,403],{},[15,404],{"alt":309,"src":405},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fj5EkcBH.png",[12,407,408,409,412,413,416],{},"What if a parameter can accept multiple types — say ",[56,410,411],{},"string"," or ",[56,414,415],{},"number","? You can write it like this:",[61,418,420],{"className":111,"code":419,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string | number } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[56,421,422,426,430,443,453,459,465,469,487,499],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,423,424],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,425,211],{"class":210},[70,427,428],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,429,216],{"class":210},[70,431,432,434,436,439,441],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,433,221],{"class":210},[70,435,224],{"class":120},[70,437,438],{"class":76}," { string | number }",[70,440,230],{"class":131},[70,442,233],{"class":210},[70,444,445,447,449,451],{"class":72,"line":236},[70,446,221],{"class":210},[70,448,199],{"class":120},[70,450,227],{"class":76},[70,452,245],{"class":210},[70,454,455,457],{"class":72,"line":248},[70,456,221],{"class":210},[70,458,352],{"class":120},[70,460,461,463],{"class":72,"line":254},[70,462,357],{"class":210},[70,464,360],{"class":210},[70,466,467],{"class":72,"line":273},[70,468,251],{"class":210},[70,470,471,473,475,477,479,481,483,485],{"class":72,"line":286},[70,472,121],{"class":120},[70,474,125],{"class":124},[70,476,128],{"class":120},[70,478,132],{"class":131},[70,480,136],{"class":135},[70,482,139],{"class":131},[70,484,142],{"class":120},[70,486,145],{"class":131},[70,488,489,491,493,495,497],{"class":72,"line":385},[70,490,151],{"class":120},[70,492,154],{"class":80},[70,494,136],{"class":131},[70,496,159],{"class":80},[70,498,162],{"class":131},[70,500,501],{"class":72,"line":398},[70,502,168],{"class":131},[12,504,505],{},[15,506],{"alt":507,"src":508},"type","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FgLjGZ5d.png",[12,510,511,512,515,516,518,519,521],{},"Here's something worth pointing out. Why do I say JSDoc is a solid choice when you can't use TypeScript? From the examples above, JSDoc clearly helps us out. But that alone is far from enough — because developers are human. You might've already written ",[56,513,514],{},"@param { string } name"," for ",[56,517,294],{},", and yet still accidentally pass a ",[56,520,415],{}," when calling it:",[61,523,525],{"className":111,"code":524,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n\nsayHi(1);\n",[56,526,527,531,535,547,557,563,569,573,591,603,607,614],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,528,529],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,530,211],{"class":210},[70,532,533],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,534,216],{"class":210},[70,536,537,539,541,543,545],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,538,221],{"class":210},[70,540,224],{"class":120},[70,542,227],{"class":76},[70,544,230],{"class":131},[70,546,233],{"class":210},[70,548,549,551,553,555],{"class":72,"line":236},[70,550,221],{"class":210},[70,552,199],{"class":120},[70,554,227],{"class":76},[70,556,245],{"class":210},[70,558,559,561],{"class":72,"line":248},[70,560,221],{"class":210},[70,562,352],{"class":120},[70,564,565,567],{"class":72,"line":254},[70,566,357],{"class":210},[70,568,360],{"class":210},[70,570,571],{"class":72,"line":273},[70,572,251],{"class":210},[70,574,575,577,579,581,583,585,587,589],{"class":72,"line":286},[70,576,121],{"class":120},[70,578,125],{"class":124},[70,580,128],{"class":120},[70,582,132],{"class":131},[70,584,136],{"class":135},[70,586,139],{"class":131},[70,588,142],{"class":120},[70,590,145],{"class":131},[70,592,593,595,597,599,601],{"class":72,"line":385},[70,594,151],{"class":120},[70,596,154],{"class":80},[70,598,136],{"class":131},[70,600,159],{"class":80},[70,602,162],{"class":131},[70,604,605],{"class":72,"line":398},[70,606,168],{"class":131},[70,608,610],{"class":72,"line":609},11,[70,611,613],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":612},true,"\n",[70,615,617,619,622,625],{"class":72,"line":616},12,[70,618,294],{"class":124},[70,620,621],{"class":131},"(",[70,623,624],{"class":84},"1",[70,626,627],{"class":131},");\n",[12,629,630],{},"That'll cause a problem, and for us devs it's an easy way to introduce bugs. So are we stuck just biting the bullet and using TypeScript? Nope — JSDoc can do type validation too. We just haven't set up our environment for it yet. So let's do that.",[20,632,634],{"id":633},"jsdoc-type-checking-and-autocomplete","JSDoc Type Checking and Autocomplete",[12,636,637,638,641],{},"First, create a ",[56,639,640],{},"jsconfig.json"," file in the project root with this content:",[61,643,647],{"className":644,"code":645,"language":646,"meta":66,"style":66},"language-json shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"checkJs\": true,\n    \"allowJs\": true\n  },\n  \"exclude\": [\"node_modules\"]\n}\n","json",[56,648,649,654,663,677,687,692,706],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,650,651],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,652,653],{"class":131},"{\n",[70,655,656,660],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,657,659],{"class":658},"sWTrB","  \"compilerOptions\"",[70,661,662],{"class":131},": {\n",[70,664,665,668,671,674],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,666,667],{"class":658},"    \"checkJs\"",[70,669,670],{"class":131},": ",[70,672,673],{"class":84},"true",[70,675,676],{"class":131},",\n",[70,678,679,682,684],{"class":72,"line":236},[70,680,681],{"class":658},"    \"allowJs\"",[70,683,670],{"class":131},[70,685,686],{"class":84},"true\n",[70,688,689],{"class":72,"line":248},[70,690,691],{"class":131},"  },\n",[70,693,694,697,700,703],{"class":72,"line":254},[70,695,696],{"class":658},"  \"exclude\"",[70,698,699],{"class":131},": [",[70,701,702],{"class":80},"\"node_modules\"",[70,704,705],{"class":131},"]\n",[70,707,708],{"class":72,"line":273},[70,709,710],{"class":131},"}\n",[12,712,713],{},"Now you should see error messages:",[12,715,716],{},[15,717],{"alt":718,"src":719},"JSDoc type validation","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FOhNxREP.png",[12,721,722],{},"And if you don't pass the parameter correctly, you'll get a warning too:",[12,724,725],{},[15,726],{"alt":727,"src":728},"JSDoc parameter validation","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fqt8lXbb.png",[12,730,731,732,734,735,737,738,741,742,744,745,747,748,751,752,755,756,763],{},"If you're a TypeScript developer, ",[56,733,640],{}," probably looks familiar — that's because ",[56,736,640],{}," is derived from ",[56,739,740],{},"tsconfig.json",". So you can use ",[56,743,740],{}," settings inside ",[56,746,640],{},", like ",[56,749,750],{},"\"target\": \"es6\"",", ",[56,753,754],{},"\"module\": \"commonjs\"",", and so on. I won't go deep into those here, but if you want to learn more, check the ",[757,758,762],"a",{"href":759,"rel":760},"https:\u002F\u002Fcode.visualstudio.com\u002Fdocs\u002Flanguages\u002Fjsconfig",[761],"nofollow","official docs",".",[20,765,767],{"id":766},"other-jsdoc-patterns","Other JSDoc Patterns",[12,769,770,771,774],{},"Now that we've covered the basics of writing JSDoc and the basic setup, let's talk about some other patterns. In real-world dev things are never this simple — you'll be dealing with arrays and objects too. So let's start with a plain variable declaration. If you want to put a type on a variable, there's a new piece of JSDoc syntax for that: ",[56,772,773],{},"@type",". Here are a few examples.",[776,777,779],"h3",{"id":778},"variable-declaration","Variable Declaration",[61,781,783],{"className":111,"code":782,"language":113,"meta":66,"style":66},"\u002F**\n * My name\n * @type { string }\n *\u002F\nconst myName = 'Ray';\n",[56,784,785,789,794,803,807],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,786,787],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,788,211],{"class":210},[70,790,791],{"class":72,"line":148},[70,792,793],{"class":210}," * My name\n",[70,795,796,798,800],{"class":72,"line":165},[70,797,221],{"class":210},[70,799,773],{"class":120},[70,801,802],{"class":76}," { string }\n",[70,804,805],{"class":72,"line":236},[70,806,251],{"class":210},[70,808,809,811,814,816,819],{"class":72,"line":248},[70,810,121],{"class":120},[70,812,813],{"class":84}," myName",[70,815,128],{"class":120},[70,817,818],{"class":80}," 'Ray'",[70,820,162],{"class":131},[12,822,823],{},[15,824],{"alt":507,"src":825},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FZ